igh","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places (in at least sixteen counties, but especially Leigh in Lancashire) named either with the nominative case of Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’ (see   Lee  ) or with <i>lēage</i>, a late dative form of this word (see   Lye  ).","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 李, based on its Cantonese pronunciation. See   Li   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Leah","meanings":["English: variant of   Leigh  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 李 and 利, see   Li   1 and 3."]},{"name":"Lee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sang, Jae, Jong, Jung, Sung, Yong, Kyung, Seung, Dong, Kwang, Myung.","English: topographic name for someone who lived near a meadow or a patch of arable land, Middle English <i>lee</i>, <i>lea</i>, from Old English <i>lēa</i>, dative case (used after a preposition) of <i>lēah</i>, which originally meant ‘wood or glade’.","English: habitational name from any of the many places in England named with Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, glade’, including Lee in Buckinghamshire, Essex, Hampshire, Kent, and Shropshire, and Lea in Cheshire, Derbyshire, Herefordshire, Lancashire, Lincolnshire, and Wiltshire."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":32,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Leigh was born in 1350, in Isel, Cumberland, England, his father, William de Legh, was 49 and his mother, Margaret Moulton, was 24. He had at least 1 son with Katherine. He died in 1394, in England, at the age of 44."},"et":{"1350–1394":"1350–1394","1356–Female":"1356–Surnud","1376–1428":"1376–1428","1302–1354":"1302–1354","1326–Female":"1326–Surnud","December 1354":"detsember 1354","1326":"1326","1302":"1302","1356":"1356","1376":"1376","1354":"1354","before 1350":"enne 1350","1350":"1350","1394":"1394","1382":"1382","1428":"1428","Isel Hall, Isel, Cockermouth, Cumbria, England":"Isel, Cumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Isel, Cumberland, England":"Isel, Cumberland, England","England":"England","Orton, Northamptonshire, England":"Orton, Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"1350–1394":"1350–1394","1356–Female":"1356–Kuollut","1376–1428":"1376–1428","1302–1354":"1302–1354","1326–Female":"1326–Kuollut","December 1354":"joulukuu 1354","1326":"1326","1302":"1302","1356":"1356","1376":"1376","1354":"1354","before 1350":"ennen vuotta 1350","1350":"1350","1394":"1394","1382":"1382","1428":"1428","Isel Hall, Isel, Cockermouth, Cumbria, England":"Isel, Cumberland, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Isel, Cumberland, England":"Isel, Cumberland, England","England":"England","Orton, Northamptonshire, England":"Orton, Northamptonshire, England"},"fr":{"1350–1394":"1350–1